Residuals Diagnostics and Variation - Week 3

Figure below shows an outlier.

It does not affect the fit that much (see orange and black lines). The outlier is said to lack influence.

Figure below shows that including the outlier changes the fit. The outlier is said to be influential.

Outilers may represent reals events or may be spurious data.

Diagnostic plots

Display Residuals versus Fitted Values

Residuals should be uncorrelated to the fit, independent and (almost) identicaly distributed with mean zero

More infor about the plot below here

plot(fit, which =1)

Residuals dont seem to be uncorrelated. Theres a linear pattern involving all but one residual and the fit.

From above, the point labelled 1 is the influential outlier.

Remove outlier from data

fitno <- lm(y ~ x, out2[-1,])

Display new Residuals vc Fitted plot

plot(fitno, which =1)

Now residuals are independently and (almost) identically distributed with zero mean and uncorrelated to the fit.

  • Check the change induced by including the influential first sample:
coef(fit) - coef(fitno)
(Intercept)           x 
-0.01167866 -0.53363019

From the above, it is clear that sample 1 has a larger effect (about 100 times of any other point) on the slope (x column) than the other samples shown.

The effect on the intercept is not very distinctive.

When a sample is included, it pulls the regression closer to itself (orange line). Its residual (difference between actual y value and the predicted y value) is smaller in magnitude than when outlier is omitted.

To compute the influence of an outlier:

head(hatvalues(fit))
         1          2          3          4          5          6 
0.63115474 0.02324999 0.01962520 0.04326099 0.02255531 0.02071441

Residuals of individual samples have different variances and these differences can become large in the presence of outliers.

#calculate the sample standard deviation of fit's residual
#it's done by dividing the fit's deviance by the residual DF and taking the sqrt
sigma <- sqrt(deviance(fit)/df.residual(fit))

Compute fits standardized residual

rstd <- resid(fit)/(sigma * sqrt(1-hatvalues(fit)))

Function rstandard does the same as above

head(cbind(rstd, rstandard(fit)))

1 -5.1928156 -5.1928156

Scale-Location

Shows the square root of standardized residuals against fitted values

plot(fit, which=3)

QQ plot of standardized residuals against normal with constant variance

plot(fit, which=2)

The outliers standardized residual (1) on the NOrmal QQ plot is about -5 standard deviations from the mean

Studentized residuals

Estimate the standard deviations of individual residuals using, in addition to individual hat values, the deviance of a model which leaves the associated sample out.

# compute sample sdev of fitno
sigma1 <- sqrt(deviance(fitno)/df.residual(fitno))

# compute studentized residual for the outlier
resid(fit)[1]/(sigma1*sqrt(1-hatvalues(fit)[1]))
        1 
-7.664261

The function rstudent calculates Studentized residuals for each sample using a procedure equivalent to that was done above

head(rstudent(fit)) 
         1          2          3          4          5          6 
-7.6642608  0.9378046  1.0460451  0.2657179  0.1874606  0.2165588

Cooks distance

It is the sum of squared differences between values fitted with and without a particular sample.

It tells how much a sample changes a model.

#difference between predicted values in fit and fitno
dy <- predict(fit, out2) - predict(fitno, out2)

# compute Cook's distance
sum(dy^2)/(2*sigma^2)
[1] 23.07105

The function cooks.distance will calculate Cooks distance for each sample

# cooks.distance(fit)[1]
plot(fit, which=5)
